<p>We will now start to think of positions of games more like numbers to analyze them algebraically. In fact, we've already started thinking about doing that when we said that Pick Up Stones 2: Electric Boogaloo was like playing two games of Pick Up Stones added together. 
</p>

<p>In situations like this, we could say that Pick Up Stones 2 with <m>n</m> and <m>m</m> stones is the same as Pick Up Stones with <m>n</m> stones <m>+</m> Pick Up Stones with <m>m</m> stones. The two games being added together are often called <term>components</term> of the game. In sums of games, on a player's turn they choose one component to play in and make one move in that game, then their turn ends. (Just like with Pick Up Stones 2)
</p>

